''Basic Math'' was reviewed in ''[[Video (magazine)|Video]]'' magazine as part of a general review of the [[Atari 2600|Atari VCS]]. The reviewer described the game as very basic mathematics and that the controls of the game were more complicated than the game itself, giving the game a ranking of five out of ten.{{sfn|Kaplan|1979|p=33}} David H. Ahl of ''[[Creative Computing (magazine)|Creative Computing]]'' also commented that a number keypad would be more suitable for the game, while enjoying the musical tune when a correct answer was given.{{sfn|Ahl|1978|p=38}}

From retrospective reviews, a reviewer from ''TV Gamer'' in 1983 said it was "an early game, now showing its age.", concluding that the educational game ''[[Math Gran Prix]]'' (1982) was better.{{sfn|Williamson|1983|p=20}} Author and video game enthusiast [[Ken Uston]] listed the game as among his least favorite from Atari in 1983.{{sfn|Uston|1983|p=68}} Skyler Miller's review in [[RhythmOne#AllGame|AllGame]] said that while ''Basic Math'' might be a good way for children to practice arithmetic, it was ultimately a low quality game due to its poor graphics and how complicated it was to adjust the different gameplay modes.{{sfn|Miller}} Brett Weiss, in his book ''Classic Home Video Games 1972-1984'' also spoke negatively about the graphics as well as a lack of a two-player mode, while finding the music jingle and timed challenges to be highlights.{{sfn|Weiss|2007|p=35}} Bunch, in his book ''Atari Archive: Vol.1 1977-1978'' wrote that the game never taught the players how to reach a correct answer, which limited it as an educational tool and that it would not be fun for either children or adults.{{sfn|Bunch|2022|p=96}}{{sfn|Bunch|2022|p=99}}

